8p3.title: Square root
8p3.clickbait: What is the opposite of multiplying a number by itself?
8p3.text:
**Why is the square root named as such?**

When you try to get the of a square %%note: A shape where all sides are equal%% and know the length of a side you multiply the length of one side by itself or square it. ![area of square](http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-hkA5woVs-NQ/VRw85xkXlDI/AAAAAAAAAFc/Xc7utStLO7E/s1600/C%2BProgram%2BArea%2BOf%2BSquare.jpg) What if you don't know the length of a side and instead only know the area of a square and want to get the length of a side? You would have to do something to the area that transforms it in the opposite direction that squaring the lenghth of a side does. Not unlike how adding 2 apples to a pile transforms a pile of apples by increasing the amount of apples and eating 2 apples transforms the pile back to the way it was. Well this kind of transformation called a Square Root.
